{"questionId":"13656","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The curve <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"C\">\n  <mi>C</mi>\n</math></span> is given by the equation <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = x\\,{\\text{tan}}\\left( {\\frac{{\\pi xy}}{4}} \\right)\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>tan</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mfrac>\n        <mrow>\n          <mi>π</mi>\n          <mi>x</mi>\n          <mi>y</mi>\n        </mrow>\n        <mn>4</mn>\n      </mfrac>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence find the equation of the normal to <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"C\"> <mi>C</mi> </math></span> at the point (1, 1).</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to use gradient of normal&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" = \\frac{{ - 1}}{{\\frac{{{\\text{d}}y}}{{{\\text{d}}x}}}}\"> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>−</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> <mi>y</mi> </mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" = \\frac{{\\pi&nbsp; - 2}}{{\\pi&nbsp; + 2}}\"> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>π</mi> <mo>−</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>π</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </math></span></p>\n<p>so equation of normal is&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y - 1 = \\frac{{\\pi&nbsp; - 2}}{{\\pi&nbsp; + 2}}\\left( {x - 1} \\right)\"> <mi>y</mi> <mo>−</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>π</mi> <mo>−</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>π</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mi>x</mi> <mo>−</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span> or&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = \\frac{{\\pi&nbsp; - 2}}{{\\pi&nbsp; + 2}}x + \\frac{4}{{\\pi&nbsp; + 2}}\"> <mi>y</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>π</mi> <mo>−</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>π</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mi>x</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mn>4</mn> <mrow> <mi>π</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13656","referenceCode":"19M.1.AHL.TZ2.H_6b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence find the equation of the normal to C at the point (1, 1).","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.4—Tangents and normal"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}